<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-962-008  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 962 008.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Dec 1989 v26 n12 p24(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technology in medicine: too much too soon?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fitzgerald, Karen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Growing cost and incomplete data on effectiveness causes manyobservers to question whether high-technology diagnostic andtreatment equipment may be over-used in the US medical community.andO;The cost of health care in 1989 absorbs 12 percent of the grossnational product, as compared with six percent in 1964.andP;  With theadvent of Medicare and health insurance, neither the patient northe doctor has an incentive to keep costs down.andP;  The Federal Foodand Drug Administration tests and regulates new products butcannot control the rate of use.andP;  Such new technology asimplantable defibrillators, magnetic resonance imaging, andcathode ray tube scanning entered the market at various rates andwith various reports of success.andP;  Among possible solutions areMedicare reforms and a payment system based on Canada's.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     High TechnologyMedicineAnalysisCost Benefit AnalysisProductsPrice.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtablechart.andO;Caption:   Medical technology costs: product, cost, procedure charge. (table)Automatic implantable defibrillator positioned in body. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>